body:
The following code reports a unique if violation when I believe it should not due to the "else null" at the end of the unique if chain.
```verilog
module tb;
    logic clk;
    logic A, B, C;
    logic reset;

    always #1 clk = ~clk;

    initial begin
        clk = 0;
        reset = 0;
        A = 0;
        B = 0;
        C = 0;
        #10;
        reset = 1;
        #2;
        A = 1;
        #10;
        $finish;
    end

    logic x;

    blah blah_i (
        .*
    );

endmodule

module blah (
    input logic reset,
    input logic clk,
    input logic A, B, C,
    output logic x
);

    always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge reset) begin
        if(!reset) begin
            x <= '0;
        end else if(A) begin
            //this would really be best as a unique0, however we've found in practice
            //that unique is fairly well-supported across a range of tools while
            //unique0 is not
            unique if(B) begin
                x <= '0;
            end else if (C) begin
                x <= '1;
            end else ;//necessary for unique if to not have a false positive
        end
    end

endmodule
```
The following functionally-equivalent module does not issue a unique if violation and uses a different style of else condition.
```verilog
    always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge reset) begin
        if(!reset) begin
            x <= '0;
        end else if(A) begin
            //this would really be best as a unique0, however we've found in practice
            //that unique is fairly well-supported across a range of tools while
            //unique0 is not
            unique if(B) begin
                x <= '0;
            end else if (C) begin
                x <= '1;
            end else begin
                ;//necessary for unique if to not have a false positive
            end
        end
    end
```

What output from that test indicates it is wrong, and what is the correct or expected output?
```
[13] %Error: unique_if_else.sv:44: Assertion failed in tb.blah_i: 'unique if' statement violated
%Error: unique_if_else.sv:44: Verilog $stop
Aborting...
```
Expected behavior: runs without error.

What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?
`verilator --timing --binary unique_if_else.sv`

What 'verilator --version' are you using?
5.040

